<br>
We ALL complain because of twinking, and the availability of melee items compared to caster items.  From this, it really doesn't make much sense that there are so few spells available in the game, and that's a large part of the problem.  Focus items should help compensate IF they are even introduced, but we SHOULD have a larger number of spells in the game, most of them being drops from mobs from levels 1 through 60.<br>
<br>
The comparison in melee weapons and armor is stats, armor class, damage, delay, proc, and right-click effects available for melee classes.  For casters, we havn't had anything that drops that affects the damage output from our spells, or how fast we can cast, or anything of that sort.  So, where's the variety of spells that cast slower, cast faster, do more damage, do less damage, have longer and shorter duration.  For rain spells, where's the versions that only last 2 waves, and those that go for 5 or 6 waves worth?  THIS would solve many problems as long as the availability is appropriate.  Melee items drop off various mobs, and while each and every spell might not be easy to get, in general we should see spells all over the place, with the better variety dropping off named mobs the way melee items do.  <br>
<br>
In short, if we have 5 level 60 spells available, we complain because of the difficulty of getting the two top spells is very very difficult.  But if we had 30 level 60 DD spells available, with only the two two, or even 5 comming off specific mobs that are very difficult, the rest being good spells, then we wouldn't have as much of a reason to complain.<br>
<br>
Sunstrike came out with 1615 damage, and dropped off a number of different level 60+ mobs.  Sure it isn't EASY to get, but it's available.  Velious gave us nothing new since Ice Spear of Solist has the lame 5 second recast delay and in general isn't an UPGRADE from Sunstrike.  So, to date, we had Ice Comet, Sunstrike, Elnerick's Electrical Rending, and Garrison's Supperior Sundering for the big blasts.  Seems that we should have seen a 1615 damage spell that would take 10 seconds to cast, and a version that could cast in 4 seconds.  Perhaps a version that casts in 3 seconds but has a recast delay, and a version that does 1800 damage, and a version that does 1400 damage.  Extend this model, spread them around, and bingo, a lot of problems are solved with class balance.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 60 Wizard<br>
The First Seal<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/7/02 2:18 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Not an upgrade</span><hr size=1> 7.0  + 2.5 1615 damage @ 450 mana (3.59 ratio)<br>
3.5 + 2.5 + 10.5 1200 damage @ 300 mana (4.0 ratio)<br>
<br>
Is it just me, or isn't spear-sunstrike-spear-sunstrike a 3.75 ratio 170.6 DPS combo?<br>
<br>
Vs 170.0 3.59 DPS from just sunstrike?<br>
<br>
I mean, isn't that an upgrade comparable to primal velium weapons?  ;-)<br>
<br>
It is 5% more efficient!<br>
<br>
hehe.<br>
<br>
The reason why there isn't that many spells is because of spell book room.  Until they get around to rewriting the PC character files (ahum), your spell book can't get bigger.<br>
<br>
They could allow you to &quot;overscribe&quot; a varient of a spell, I guess.  Would you get the old spell you had scribed back?  If not, they'd have to publish more details of spells in-game, or people would get all upset when they downgraded a good spell.  Hell, the'll get upset even IF they publish more details of spells.<br>
<br>
...<br>
<br>
Oooo, they could allow you to unscribe spells to NO DROP, rescribeable versions of a spell.  It would solve the space&amp;clutter problems in spellbooks!<br>
